issue(id="0006" status="review")
  title Explore porting notes and task files to Pug
  user-story
    as-a maintainer working across Markdown notes and Pug task files
    i-want to finish validating the new split between selectively retained Markdown docs and Pug-authored task records
    so-that the repo can keep raw-readable prose where it helps while standardizing structured work items around a more ergonomic shape
  premise.
    The repo now keeps human-authored prose notes as Markdown where that still
    feels like the best raw-readable format, while structured work items have
    been ported to Pug. That is already a meaningful simplification for task
    authoring, but it still leaves an open question about how broadly Pug
    should spread beyond the task system and how much additional tooling or
    workflow support the new shape deserves.

    The task-file side of the migration is no longer hypothetical. The Pug
    task shape is readable enough in raw form that it now serves as the
    canonical workflow artifact. The remaining exploration is narrower:
    whether selected Markdown notes should also move, what conventions should
    govern those decisions, and how diffs, editor ergonomics, formatting, and
    agent ingestion behave once Pug is part of normal authoring.

    With the likely exception of README-style files, the purpose of these
    notes is not primarily to render them into another presentation layer. The
    raw files themselves are the product: humans read them directly in editors
    and terminals, and agents ingest them as source material. That means a Pug
    proposal should be treated skeptically if it depends on a render step for
    ordinary use, weakens raw-file readability, or introduces tooling that
    makes the canonical text less accessible than today's Markdown and XML.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion The repo has a written evaluation of Pug as a source format for note-like documents in a world where task records are already canonically authored in Pug.
    criterion The evaluation compares at least three note strategies: keep Markdown as-is, use Pug only for selected note classes, or adopt a broader Pug-centered note model, while treating render-dependent workflows as a poor fit outside README-like exceptions.
    criterion The exploration identifies how metadata, headings, lists, code blocks, and other note-oriented structure would be represented without losing important readability or validation properties.
    criterion The work evaluates raw-file readability and agent-ingestion ergonomics as first-class requirements, including whether a maintainer can comfortably read and edit representative files without compiling or previewing them.
    criterion The work includes a concrete proposal for how review ergonomics, formatting, and automation would function, including whether `dprint` can format the chosen source shape directly or would need new plugins, custom tooling, or an intentional gap.
    criterion The exploration records whether Pug has solid syntax-highlighting and editing support in the editors we actually favor, and treats weak editor support as a meaningful strike against migration.
    criterion If broader note migration still looks viable, the task leaves behind a narrow pilot plan for one representative Markdown note before any wider conversion is attempted.
  review-items
    item(status="open").
      Decide whether Pug should remain specific to structured task records or
      expand into selected note types where the raw-reading experience stays
      strong enough.
    item(status="open").
      Compare raw-file readability carefully, since the remaining question is
      about notes that are meant to be read directly by humans and ingested
      directly by agents.
    item(status="open").
      Check formatter and editor support early, especially whether `dprint`
      can participate and whether favored editors offer dependable syntax
      highlighting and editing behavior for Pug.
    item(status="open").
      Identify the smallest realistic note pilot so the evaluation can test
      author experience, diff quality, automation burden, and ingestion
      ergonomics before touching the broader corpus.
